author: Amit_Kalra;
title: 3 creative ways to fix fashion's waste problem

aws-transcripts.transcript: a few years ago, I found myself looking for the most cost effective way to be stylish. So naturally, I wound up on my local thrift store, a wonderland of other people's trash that was ripe to be plucked. Become my treasure. I wasn't just looking for your average off the second hand rack vintage T shirt to wear. For me, Real style lives at the intersection of design and individuality. So to make sure that I was getting the most out of the things that I was finding about a sewing machine so I could tailor the 90 style garments that I was finding to fit a more contemporary aesthetic. I've been tailoring and make my own clothes from scratch ever since, so everything in my closet is uniquely my own. But as I was sorting through the endless racks of clothes of these thrift stores, I start to ask myself what happens all the clothes. I don't buy the stuff that isn't really cool or trendy, but kind of sits there and rots away at the second hand stores. I work in the fashion industry on the wholesale side, and I start to see some of the products that we sell end up on the racks of these thrift stores, so the questions start to work its way into my work life as well. I did some research, and I pretty quickly found a very scary supply chain that led me to some pretty troubling realities. It turned out that the clothes that I was sorting through at these thrift stores represented only a small fraction of the total amount of garments that we dispose of each year in the U. S. Only 15% of the total textile and garment waste that's generated each year ends up being donated or recycled in some way, which means that the other 85% of textile and garment waste end up in landfills every year. Now I want to put this into perspective because I don't quite think that that 85% does the problem justice. This means that almost 13,000,000 tons of clothing and textile waste end up in landfills every year. In just the United States alone. This averages out to be roughly 200 T shirts per person ending up in the garden fish in Canada. We throw away enough clothing to fill the largest stadium in my hometown of Toronto, one that seats 60,000 people with a mountain of clothes three times the size of that stadium. Now, even with this, I still think that Canadians are the more polite North Americans, so don't hold it against us. What was even more surprising was seeing that the fashion industry is the second largest polluter in the world, behind the oil and gas industry. Now this is an important comparison to make. I don't wanna defend the oil and gas industry, but I'd be lying if I said that. I was surprised to hear that they were the number one polluter. I just assumed, fairly or not. But that's an industry that doesn't really mind sticking to the status quo one where the technology doesn't really change and the focus is more so on driving profitability at the expense of a sustainable future. But I was really surprised to see that the fashion industry with number two, because maintaining the status quo is the opposite of what the fashion industry stands for. The unfortunate reality is not only do we waste a lot of things that we do consume, but we also use a lot to produce the clothes that we buy each year. On average, household's purchase of clothing per year requires 1000 bathtubs of water to produce 1000 bathtubs of water per household per year. That's a lot of water.
